Flaminius, -i‚ m.: Caius, Consul for the year 217 B.C. He was hated by the nobles and senators because osan agrarian law carried by him in 232 Bc, by which the Picentine territory was distributed among the plebeians. It madc him very popular with the people (plebs); and he was twice elected Consul, 223 nc. and 217 B.c. Fearing that the second election would be set aside, he left the city secretly and hurried to Ariminum to take over Sempronius’ army, omitting to perform the customary sacrifices and vows. He declined to return when bidden to do so by the Senate, and in the following campaign he was surprised at Lake Trasimenus, in Etruria, and cut to pieces with almost the whole of his army.

Gades, -ium, f. pL: the name of an island and town of Hispania Baetica, now Cadiz, between the Straits of Gibraltar and the mouth of the Baetis (Guadalquiver). Hannibal marched thither with his army in the early spring of 218 B.c. to redcem his old vows in the temple of Hercules (Melcarth), and to take new ones (cap. 21).
